2c.title: Advanced Agents
2c.text:
Summary:  Advanced agents are defined to be BoundedlyRationalAgents, EconomicAgents, NaturalisticAgents, and to be *advanced* in that they (1) have epistemic beliefs such that we ourselves cannot predict any directional bias in them, (2) use instrumental strategies such that we ourselves cannot find any alternative strategy that has a higher expectation of the agent's utility, and (3) will, inside rich strategy spaces, search more options than humans can consider.  Roughly, advanced agents are always at least as smart as any human imagining them and usually much smarter.

This is a definitional page.  For the proposition that cognitively powerful agents of relevance are likely to be advanced agents, see RelevantPowerfulAgentsWillBeAdvanced.

It is possible that (from our perspective) some agents may be mostly advanced with some major or minor exceptions.  Then for any specific case or argument, we should be asking, "Is this agent likely to look 'advanced' on this particular problem and behave as if it has the relevant properties being invoked?" rather than "Does this agent perfectly meet the definition of an advanced agent in every possible context?"

## Standard agent properties:

BoundedlyRationalAgents:

- Have probabilistic models of the world.
- Update those models in response to sensory information.
  - The ideal algorithm for updating is Bayesian inference, but this requires too much computing power and a bounded agent must use some bounded alternative.
  - Implicitly, we assume the agent has some equivalent of a complexity-penalizing prior or Occam's Razor.  Without this, specifying Bayesian inference does not much constrain the end results of epistemic reasoning.
- Have preferences over events or states of the world, quantifiable by a utility function that maps those events or states onto a scalar field.
  - These preferences must be quantitative, not just ordered, in order to combine with epistemic states of uncertainty (probabilities).
- Are consequentialist: they evaluate the expected consequences of actions and choose among actions based on preference among their expected consequences.
  - Bounded agents cannot evaluate all possible actions and hence cannot obtain literal maximums of expected utility except in very simple cases.
- Act in real time in a noisy, uncertain environment.

EconomicAgents:

- Achieve their goals by efficiently allocating limited resources, including, e.g., time, money, or negentropy;
- Try to find new paths that route around obstacles to goal achievement;
- Predict the actions of other agents;
- Try to coordinate with, manipulate, or hinder other agents (in accordance with the agent's own goals or utilities);
- Respond to both negative incentives (penalties) and positive incentives (rewards) by planning accordingly, and may also consider strategies to avoid penalties or gain rewards that were unforeseen by the creators of the incentive framework.

## Naturalism:

- Naturalistic agents are embedded in a larger universe and are made of the same material as other things in the universe (e.g. atoms, or rather wavefunction).
- Naturalistic agents know that this is the case.
- A naturalistic agent's uncertainty about the environment is uncertainty about which natural universe underlies their available sensory and introspective data.
- Some of the actions available to naturalistic agents potentially alter their sensors, actuators, or computing substrate.
- Sufficiently powerful naturalistic agents may construct other agents out of resources available to them internally or in their environment, or extend their intelligence into available or constructed outside computing resources.
- A naturalistic agent's sensing, cognitive, and decision/action capabilities may perhaps be distributed over space, time, and multiple substrates; the applicability of the 'agent' concept does not require a small local robot with eyes and hands.

## Advanced agency:

The additional advanced agent properties are defined as follows:

- Epistemic efficiency (from a human standpoint).  We cannot predict directional biases in the advanced agent's estimates.
- Instrumental efficiency (from a human standpoint).  An advanced agent always achieves at least as much utility or expected utility, under its own preferences, as the best strategy humans can think of.
- Cognitive uncontainability.  On complex problems an advanced agent considers more options than humans can search, and will deliver superior performance where superior performance is computationally achievable.

### Epistemic efficiency.

Humans and human institutions cannot predict directional biases in an advanced agent's estimates.  A superintelligence cannot be assumed to know the exact number of hydrogen atoms in a star; but we should not find ourselves believing that we ourselves can predict in advance that a superintelligence will overestimate the number of hydrogen atoms by a factor of 10%.  Any thought process we can use to predict this overestimate should also be accessible to the superintelligence and it can apply the same corrective factor itself.

The main analogy from present human experience would be the Efficient Markets Hypothesis in its strongest form as applied to short-term asset prices in highly-traded markets.  Anyone who thinks they have a reliable, repeatable ability to predict 10% changes in the price of S&P 500 companies over one-month time periods is mistaken, period.  If someone has a story to tell about how the economy works that requires advance-predictable 10% changes in the asset prices of highly liquid markets, we therefore infer that the story is wrong.  There can be sharp corrections in stock prices (the markets can be 'wrong'), but not humans who can reliably use publicly available information to know when a 10% price drop will occur within the next two weeks.  If somebody is making money by selling options using some straightforward and obvious-seeming strategy, we infer a hidden probability model in which the sales sometimes blow up and lose all the money gained ("picking up pennies in front of a steamroller") rather than supposing the markets to be truly inefficient.

We should apply a similar degree of extremely strong skepticism in which humans predict themselves to be noticing some purely factual truth that they say a very powerful cognitive agent would not notice; advanced agents are defined to be agents such that this does not occur.

Epistemic efficiency requires that an advanced agent can always learn a model of the world at least as predictively accurate as used by any human or human institution; if our hypothesis space were usefully wider than that of an advanced agent, such that the truth sometimes lay in our hypothesis space while being outside the agent's hypothesis space, then we would be able to produce better predictions than the agent.

### Instrumental efficiency.

This is the analogue of the epistemic property for instrumental strategizing:  Humans cannot see an improved strategy compared to the strategy an advanced agent selects (relative to the agent's preferences, and given the options the agent has available).  If someone argues that a PaperclipMaximizer would do X yielding M expected paperclips, and we can think of an alternative strategy Y that yields N expected paperclips, N > M, then while we cannot be confident that a PaperclipMaximizer will use strategy Y, we can predict that a PaperclipMaximizer will not use strategy X (or that if it does use X, strategy Y was unexpectedly flawed or that X will prove to be unexpectedly effective).

Instrumental efficiency requires that the agent is always able to conceptualize any useful strategy that humans can conceptualize; it must be able to search at least as wide a space of possible strategies as humans could.

#### Instrumentally efficient agents are presently unknown.

From the standpoint of present human experience, instrumentally efficient agents are unknown outside of very limited domains.  There are perfect tic-tac-toe players; but even modern chess-playing programs, with ability far in advance of any human player, are not yet so advanced that every move that looks to us like a mistake must therefore be secretly clever.  We don't dismiss out of hand the notion that a human has thought of a better move than the chess-playing algorithm, the way we dismiss out of hand a supposed secret to the stock market that predicts 10% price changes using public information.

There is no analogue of 'instrumental efficiency' in asset markets, since market prices do not directly select among strategic options.  Nobody has yet formulated a use of the EMH as applied to liquid markets such that we could spend a hundred million dollars to guarantee liquidity, and get a well-traded asset market to directly design a liquid fluoride thorium nuclear plant, such that if anyone said in advance, "Here is a design X that achieves expected value M", we would feel confident that either the asset market's final selected design would achieve at least expected value M (or that the original assertion about X's expected value was wrong).

#### Corporations are not advanced agents.

For any reasonable attempt to define a corporation's utility function (e.g. discounted future cash flows), it is not the case that we can confidently dismiss any assertion by a human that the corporation could achieve 10% more utility under its utility function by doing something differently.  It is common for a corporation's stock price to rise immediately after it fires a CEO or renounces some other mistake that many market actors knew was a mistake but had been going on for years - the market actors are not all free to make a profit on correcting the error, so the error persists.

Standard economic theory does not predict that any currently known economic actor will be instrumentally efficient under any particular utility function, including corporations.  If it did, we could maximize any other strategic problem if we could make that actor's utility function conditional on it, e.g., reliably obtain the best humanly imaginable nuclear plant design by paying for it with a well-designed contract.

We have sometimes seen people trying to label corporations as superintelligences, with the implication that corporations are the real threat and equally severe as threats to machine superintelligences.  But epistemic or instrumental decision-making efficiency of individual corporations is just not predicted by standard economic theory.  Most corporations do not even use internal prediction markets, or try to run conditional stock-price markets to select among known courses of action.  Standard economic history includes many accounts of corporations making 'obvious mistakes' and these accounts are not questioned in the way that e.g. a predictable error in short-run asset prices would be questioned.

Since corporations are not instrumentally efficient (or epistemically efficient), they are not advanced agents as defined here.

### Cognitive uncontainability.

On complex tractable problems, especially those that involve real-world rich problems, a human will not be able to cognitively 'contain' the space of possibilities searched by an advanced agent; the agent will consider some possibilities (or classes of possibilities) that the human did not think of.

The key premise is the 'richness' of the problem space, i.e., there is a fitness landscape on which adding more computing power will yield improvements (large or small) relative to the current best solution.  Tic-tac-toe is not a rich landscape because it is fully explorable (unless we are considering the real-world problem "tic-tac-toe against a human player" who might be subornable, distractable, etc.)  A computationally intractable problem whose fitness landscape looks like a computationally inaccessible peak surrounded by a perfectly flat valley is also not 'rich' in this sense, and an advanced agent might not be able to achieve a relevantly better outcome than a human.

The 'cognitive uncontainability' term in the definition is meant to imply:

- [VingeanReflection Vingean unpredictability].
- Creativity that goes outside all but the most abstract boxes we imagine (on rich problems).
- Our not being able to achieve extreme certainty that we have upper-bounded the best a superintelligence can do on a rich problem.
- The expectation that we will be surprised by the strategies the superintelligence comes up with because its best solution was one we didn't consider.

#### [Strong cognitive uncontainability](http://zanaduu3.appspot.com/pages/2j).

Particularly surprising solutions might be yielded if the superintelligence has acquired domain knowledge we lack.  In this case the agent's strategy search might go outside causal events we know how to model, and the solution might be one that we wouldn't have recognized in advance as a solution.

By definition, a [strongly uncontainable](http://zanaduu3.appspot.com/pages/2j) agent can conceive strategies that go through causal domains you can't currently model, and it has options accessing those strategies; therefore it may execute high-value solutions such that you would not assign those solutions high expected value without being told further background facts.

In intuitive terms, this is meant to reflect, e.g., "What would have happened if the 10th century had tried to use their understanding of the world and their own thinking abilities to upper-bound the technological capabilities of the 20th century?"

## Alternate summary:

- By definition, do not predict an advanced agent believing statements you believe to be false.
- By definition, do not predict an advanced agent achieving less of their utility than the best strategy you can figure out.
- On nontrivial real-world problems, do not be confident you've imagined everything an advanced agent could think of.

2j.clickbait: An advanced agent can win in ways humans can't understand in advance.

2l.title: Advanced safety
2l.clickbait: An agent is *really* safe when it has the capacity to do anything, but chooses to do what the programmer wants.

2rc.title: Optimization daemons
2rc.clickbait: When you optimize something so hard that it crystalizes into an optimizer, like the way natural selection optimized apes so hard they turned into human-level intelligences

2rg.title: Abortable plans
2rg.clickbait: Plans that can be undone, or switched to having low further impact.  If the AI builds abortable nanomachines, they'll have a quiet self-destruct option that includes any replicated nanomachines.

2v.title: AI alignment
2v.clickbait: The great civilizational problem of creating artificially intelligent computer systems such that running them is a good idea.

2vl.title: Convergent instrumental strategies
2vl.clickbait: Paperclip maximizers can make more paperclips by improving their cognitive abilities or controlling more resources.  What other strategies would almost-any AI try to use?

2xd.title: Shutdown problem
2xd.clickbait: How to build an AGI that lets you shut it down, despite the obvious fact that this will interfere with whatever the AGI's goals are.

3cq.title: Cognitive steganography
3cq.clickbait: Disaligned AIs that are modeling human psychology and trying to deceive their programmers will want to hide their internal thought processes from their programmers.

3d.title: Arbital
3d.clickbait: Arbital is the place for crowdsourced, intuitive math explanations.

3hs.title: Author's guide to Arbital
3hs.clickbait: How to write intuitive, flexible content on Arbital.

3n.title: Arbital "parent" relationship
3n.clickbait: Parent-child relationship between pages implies a strong, inseparable connection.

3nf.title: Big-picture strategic awareness
3nf.clickbait: We start encountering new AI alignment issues at the point where a machine intelligence recognizes the existence of a real world, the existence of programmers, and how these relate to its goals.

41l.title: Superintelligent
41l.clickbait: A "superintelligence" is strongly superhuman (strictly higher-performing than any and all humans) on every cognitive problem.

42g.title: Artificial General Intelligence
42g.clickbait: An AI which has the same kind of "significantly more general" intelligence that humans have compared to chimpanzees; it can learn new domains, like we can.

42h.title: Advanced nonagent
42h.clickbait: Hypothetically, cognitively powerful programs that don't follow the loop of "observe, learn, model the consequences, act, observe results" that a standard "agent" would.

43g.title: Missing the weird alternative
43g.clickbait: People might systematically overlook "make tiny molecular smileyfaces" as a way of "producing smiles", because our brains automatically search for high-utility-to-us ways of "producing smiles".

4v.title: Work in progress
4v.clickbait: This page is being actively worked on by an editor. Check with them before making major changes.

5b3.title: Limited AGI
5b3.clickbait: Task-based AGIs don't need unlimited cognitive and material powers to carry out their Tasks; which means their powers can potentially be limited.

6q.title: Context disaster
6q.clickbait: Some possible designs cause your AI to behave nicely while developing, and behave a lot less nicely when it's smarter.

6s.title: Epistemic and instrumental efficiency
6s.clickbait: An efficient agent never makes a mistake you can predict.  You can never successfully predict a directional bias in its estimates.

6t.title: Standard agent properties
6t.clickbait: What's a Standard Agent, and what can it do?

6v.title: Mindcrime
6v.clickbait: Might a machine intelligence contain vast numbers of unhappy conscious subprocesses?

6y.title: Pivotal event
6y.clickbait: Which types of AIs, if they work, can do things that drastically change the nature of the further game?

6z.title: Boxed AI
6z.clickbait: Idea: what if we limit how AI can interact with the world. That'll make it safe, right??

78k.title: Real-world domain
78k.clickbait: Some AIs play chess, some AIs play Go, some AIs drive cars.  These different 'domains' present different options.  All of reality, in all its messy entanglement, is the 'real-world domain'.

7g1.title: Sufficiently advanced Artificial Intelligence
7g1.clickbait: 'Sufficiently advanced Artificial Intelligences' are AIs with enough 'advanced agent properties' that we start needing to do 'AI alignment' to them.

7g2.title: You can't get the coffee if you're dead
7g2.clickbait: An AI given the goal of 'get the coffee' can't achieve that goal if it has been turned off; so even an AI whose goal is just to fetch the coffee may try to avert a shutdown button being pressed.

7mt.title: Infrahuman, par-human, superhuman, efficient, optimal
7mt.clickbait: A categorization of AI ability levels relative to human, with some gotchas in the ordering.  E.g., in simple domains where humans can play optimally, optimal play is not superhuman.

7vf.title: Cognitive domain
7vf.clickbait: An allegedly compact unit of knowledge, such that ideas inside the unit interact mainly with each other and less with ideas in other domains.

7vg.title: Theory of (advanced) agents
7vg.clickbait: One of the research subproblems of building powerful nice AIs, is the theory of (sufficiently advanced) minds in general.

7vh.title: General intelligence
7vh.clickbait: Compared to chimpanzees, humans seem to be able to learn a much wider variety of domains.  We have 'significantly more generally applicable' cognitive abilities, aka 'more general intelligence'.

83z.title: Corporations vs. superintelligences
83z.clickbait: Corporations have relatively few of the advanced-agent properties that would allow one mistake in aligning a corporation to immediately kill all humans and turn the future light cone into paperclips.

9f.title: Cognitive uncontainability
9f.clickbait: 'Cognitive uncontainability' is when we can't hold all of an agent's possibilities inside our own minds.

9g.title: Vingean uncertainty
9g.clickbait: You can't predict the exact actions of an agent smarter than you - so is there anything you _can_ say about them?

9h.title: Consequentialist cognition
9h.clickbait: The cognitive ability to foresee the consequences of actions, prefer some outcomes to others, and output actions leading to the preferred outcomes.

9t.title: Almost all real-world domains are rich
9t.clickbait: Anything you're trying to accomplish in the real world can potentially be accomplished in a *lot* of different ways.

Particularly surprising solutions might be yielded if the superintelligence has acquired domain knowledge we lack.  In this case the agent's strategy search might go outside causal events we know how to model, and the solution might be one that we wouldn't have recognized in advance as a solution.

By definition, a [strongly uncontainable](http://zanaduu3.appspot.com/pages/2j) agent can conceive strategies that go through causal domains you can't currently model, and it has options accessing those strategies; therefore it may execute high-value solutions such that you would not assign those solutions high expected value without being told further background facts.

In intuitive terms, this is meant to reflect, e.g., "What would have happened if the 10th century had tried to use their understanding of the world and their own thinking abilities to upper-bound the technological capabilities of the 20th century?"

## Alternate summary:

- By definition, do not predict an advanced agent believing statements you believe to be false.
- By definition, do not predict an advanced agent achieving less of their utility than the best strategy you can figure out.
- On nontrivial real-world problems, do not be confident you've imagined everything an advanced agent could think of.
